{"title_page": "Nichelle Tramble Spellman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Nichelle Tramble Spellman\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_place = [[Alameda County, California]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = USA\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = television writer, showrunner, and producer\n}} \n'''Nichelle Tramble Spellman''' is an [[American people|American]] [[television producer]], showrunner and Writer.\n\nNichelle Tramble Spellman is the creator and showrunner of the [[Apple TV+]] drama series ''[[Truth Be Told (2019 TV series)|Truth Be Told]]'', starring [[Octavia Spencer]], [[Aaron Paul]], [[Lizzy Caplan]], [[Elizabeth Perkins]], [[Ron Cephas Jones]], [[Mekhi Phifer]], [[Michael Beach]], [[Tracie Thoms]], and [[Annabella Sciorra]]. The limited series is inspired by the novel, ''[[Are you sleeping (TV series)|Are You Sleeping]]''.\n\nPrevious to that, she spent three seasons on the critically-acclaimed CBS drama ''[[The Good Wife (TV series)|The Good Wife]]'', as well as FX's ''[[Justified (TV series)|Justified]]''.\n\nSpellman is also the author of the novels, ''[[The Dying Ground]]'' and ''[[The Last King]]'' published by Random House/Ballantine.\n\nShe is currently a consulting producer on FX's ''[[Snowfall (TV series)|Snowfall]]''.\n\n''Truth Be Told'' debuted on Apple TV+ on December 6, 2019. In February 2020, Spellman won the [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Writing in a Dramatic Series]] for \"Monster\", the first episode of the series.<ref name=\"THR NAACP 2020-02-22\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2020-naacp-image-award-winners-complete-list-updating-1276771/item/outstanding-writing-a-dramatic-series-1276868 |title=NAACP Image Awards: Lizzo Named Entertainer of the Year; ''Just Mercy'', ''Black-ish'' Among Top Winners |first1=Katherine |last1=Schaffstall |first2=Annie |last2=Howard |date=February 22, 2020 |accessdate=February 24, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spellman, Nichelle Tramble}}\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Nichelle Tramble Spellman\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_place = [[Alameda County, California]]\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = USA\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = television writer, showrunner, and producer\n}} \n'''Nichelle Tramble Spellman''' is an [[American people|American]] [[television producer]], showrunner and Writer.\n\nNichelle Tramble Spellman is the creator and showrunner of the [[Apple TV+]] drama series ''[[Truth Be Told (2019 TV series)|Truth Be Told]]'', starring [[Octavia Spencer]], [[Aaron Paul]], [[Lizzy Caplan]], [[Elizabeth Perkins]], [[Ron Cephas Jones]], [[Mekhi Phifer]], [[Michael Beach]], [[Tracie Thoms]], and [[Annabella Sciorra]]. The limited series is inspired by the novel, ''[[Are you sleeping (TV series)|Are You Sleeping]]''.\n\nPrevious to that, she spent three seasons on the critically-acclaimed CBS drama ''[[The Good Wife (TV series)|The Good Wife]]'', as well as FX's ''[[Justified (TV series)|Justified]]''.\n\nSpellman is also the author of the novels, ''[[The Dying Ground]]'' and ''[[The Last King]]'' published by Random House/Ballantine.\n\nShe is currently a consulting producer on FX's ''[[Snowfall (TV series)|Snowfall]]''.\n\n''Truth Be Told'' debuted on Apple TV+ on December 6, 2019. In February 2020, Spellman won the [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Writing in a Dramatic Series]] for \"Monster\", the first episode of the series.<ref name=\"THR NAACP 2020-02-22\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2020-naacp-image-award-winners-complete-list-updating-1276771/item/outstanding-writing-a-dramatic-series-1276868 |title=NAACP Image Awards: Lizzo Named Entertainer of the Year; ''Just Mercy'', ''Black-ish'' Among Top Winners |first1=Katherine |last1=Schaffstall |first2=Annie |last2=Howard |date=February 22, 2020 |accessdate=February 24, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spellman, Nichelle Tramble}}\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nichelle_Tramble_Spellman"}
{"title_page": "Nia DaCosta", "text_new": "{{Short description|American screenwriter and director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nia DaCosta\n| image              = http://www.undertheradarmag.com/uploads/article_images/niadacosta.jpg\n| birth_date         = November 8, 1989 (age 30)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NiaDaCosta/status/1236160555569655808|title=Birthday Correction}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = Brooklyn, New York\n| education          = [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts|Tisch School of the Arts]]\n| occupation         = Film director, Screenwriter\n}}\n'''Nia DaCosta''' (November 8, 1989) is an American screenwriter and director. She is known for her breakout film ''[[Little Woods]]'' (2019). Her other credits include directing two episodes of the British television series ''[[Top Boy]]'' (2019), and directing and co-writing [[Candyman (2020 film)|''Candyman'']] (2020), an upcoming direct sequel to the [[Candyman (1992 film)|1992 film of the same name]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nDaCosta was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York and raised in [[Harlem]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/04/little-woods-nia-dacosta-tessa-thompson-neon-1202059462/|title=How Nia DaCosta Went From Wide-Eyed NYU Film Grad to Hollywood Director on the Rise|last=Obenson|first=Tambay|date=April 18, 2019|website=IndieWire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She always knew she wanted to be a writer, but it wasn't until she watched ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'' (1979) that she became interested in filmmaking. This led DaCosta to research 1970s film where she found inspiration in directors such as [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Sidney Lumet]], [[Steven Spielberg]] and [[Francis Ford Coppola]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Citing Scorsese as a top inspiration, DaCosta enrolled at him alma mater, [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts]]. There she met Scorsese while working as a TV production assistant.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter finishing school and working as a TV production assistant, DaCosta's script for ''[[Little Woods]]'' was one of the 12 projects chosen for the 2015 [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]] Screenwriters and Directors Labs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/blogs/news/sundance-institute-announces-12-projects-for-2015-january-screenwriters-lab|title=Sundance Institute Announces 12 Projects for 2015 January Screenwriters Lab|last=|first=|date=September 16, 2014|website=Sundance Institute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> DaCosta funded the film through [[Kickstarter]] with the help of 72 backers who eventually raised $5,100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1451542035/little-woods-by-nia-dacosta|title=Little Woods by Nia DaCosta|last=DaCosta|first=Nia|date=December 17, 2014|website=Kickstarter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===''Little Woods''===\n''[[Little Woods]]'' tells the story of Ollie ([[Tessa Thompson]]) a reformed drug runner in rural North Dakota and her estranged sister Deb ([[Lily James]]). When their mother dies, Deb shows up on Ollie's doorstep with her young son, and reveals she is pregnant. This pushes Ollie to seek out a way to quickly raise money to pay back the bank and keep their mother\u2019s home, and pushes Deb to decide whether or not she wants to go through with getting an abortion.\n\nThe film premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] in 2018, and was awarded the [[Nora Ephron]] award for \"excellence in storytelling by a female writer or director.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tribeca-announces-nora-ephron-award-440516|title=Tribeca Announces Nora Ephron Award|last=Schillaci|first=Sophie|date=April 16, 2013|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was then bought by [[Neon (distributor)|Neon]] and distributed through [[North America]] in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/little-woods-tessa-thompson-lily-james-nia-dacosta-neon-1202410650/|title=Neon Acquires Nia DaCosta\u2019s \u2018Little Woods\u2019 After Tribeca Bow|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=June 14, 2018|website=Deadline|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> DaCosta cites [[Debra Granik|Debrah Granik's]]  ''[[Winter's Bone]]'' and [[Courtney Hunt|Courtney Hunt's]] ''[[Frozen River]]'' as being her main sources of inspiration for the script, as she feels that their films relay amazing performances and tense drama, yet tackle real issues in America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filminquiry.com/tribeca-review-little-woods/|title=Tribeca Review & Interviews: LITTLE WOODS: A Confident Debut|last=Strouse|first=Kristy|date=May 4, 2018|website=Film Inquiry|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In a 2018 interview with FF2 Media, DaCosta stated the importance to her of telling the stories of \"women...who are active\" rather than passive figures in movies led by men.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coffin |first1=Lesley |title=Nora Ephron winner Nia DaCosta talks \u2018Little Woods\u2019 |url=http://ff2media.com/blog/2018/04/29/nora-ephron-winner-nia-dacosta-on-little-woods/ |website=FF2 Media |publisher=FF2 Media |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Candyman''===\n{{main|Candyman (2020 film)}}\nIt was announced in late 2018 that DaCosta was chosen to helm what has been described as a [[Spiritual successor|spiritual sequel]] to the original [[Candyman (1992 film)|''Candyman'']] (1992). The film is said to return to the [[Chicago]] neighborhood where the legend began, yet it is now [[Gentrification|gentrified]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/candyman-reboot-nia-dacosta-jordan-peele-1203037897/|title=Jordan Peele-Produced \u2018Candyman\u2019 Reboot Taps Director Nia DaCosta|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=November 27, 2018|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The film is being produced by [[Jordan Peele]] through [[Monkeypaw Productions|Monkeypaw productions]], with Peele citing the original as \"a landmark film for black representation in the horror genre.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]] is set to star in the film,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/jordan-peele-candyman-cast-yahya-abdul-mateen-villain.html|title=Jordan Peele\u2019s Candyman Has Found Its Hook-Handed Villain|last=Crucchiola|first=Jordan|date=February 26, 2019|website=Vulture|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> with [[Tony Todd]] returning as the film's [[Candyman (character)|titular villain]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/candyman-yahya-abdul-mateen-tony-todd/|title='Candyman' Director Confirms Yahya Abdul-Mateen II Is Not Replacing Tony Todd|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|date=2019-03-25|website=Collider|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> with [[Teyonah Parris]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/beale-street-actress-teyonah-parris-join-yahya-abdul-mateen-candyman-1191801|title='Beale Street' Actress Teyonah Parris in Talks to Join Yahya Abdul-Mateen in 'Candyman' (Exclusive)|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=March 1, 2018|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[Nathan Stewart-Jarrett]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/colman-domingo-joins-teyonah-parris-in-jordan-peeles-candyman-reboot|title=Angels in America's Nathan Stewart-Jarrett is also part of the film's cast, now in production in Chicago.|last=Clement|first=Olivia|date=August 14, 2019|website=Playlist|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> set to star alongside him. [[Universal Pictures]] plans to release the film theatrically on June 12, 2020, with production beginning in the spring of 2019, and wrapping in September.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=10156310586906968&id=45586511967&substory_index=0|title=CANDYMAN|last=Abdul-Mateen II|first=Yahya|date=September 25, 2019|website=Facebook|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Work\n!Position\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Little Woods]]''\n|Writer, director\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Top Boy]]''\n|Director (Series 3, episodes 4 & 5)\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Candyman (2020 film)|Candyman]]''\n|Director, co-writer\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.niadacosta.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=4804442}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DaCosta, Nia}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:African-American television directors]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American screenwriter and director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Nia DaCosta\n| image              = http://www.undertheradarmag.com/uploads/article_images/niadacosta.jpg\n| birth_date         = November 8, 1989 (age 30)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NiaDaCosta/status/1236160555569655808|title=Birthday Correction}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = Brooklyn, New York\n| education          = [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts|Tisch School of the Arts]]\n| occupation         = Film director, Screenwriter\n}}\n'''Nia DaCosta''' (November 8, 1989) is an American screenwriter and director. She is known for her breakout film ''[[Little Woods]]'' (2019). Her other credits include directing two episodes of the British television series ''[[Top Boy]]'' (2019), and directing and co-writing [[Candyman (2020 film)|''Candyman'']] (2020), an upcoming direct sequel to the [[Candyman (1992 film)|1992 film of the same name]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Early life and education ==\nDaCosta was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York and raised in [[Harlem]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/04/little-woods-nia-dacosta-tessa-thompson-neon-1202059462/|title=How Nia DaCosta Went From Wide-Eyed NYU Film Grad to Hollywood Director on the Rise|last=Obenson|first=Tambay|date=April 18, 2019|website=IndieWire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She always knew she wanted to be a writer, but it wasn't until she watched ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'' (1979) that she became interested in filmmaking. This led DaCosta to research 1970s film where she found inspiration in directors such as [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Sidney Lumet]], [[Steven Spielberg]] and [[Francis Ford Coppola]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Citing Scorsese as a top inspiration, DaCosta enrolled at him alma mater, [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts]]. There she met Scorsese while working as a TV production assistant.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter finishing school and working as a TV production assistant, DaCosta's script for ''[[Little Woods]]'' was one of the 12 projects chosen for the 2015 [[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]] Screenwriters and Directors Labs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sundance.org/blogs/news/sundance-institute-announces-12-projects-for-2015-january-screenwriters-lab|title=Sundance Institute Announces 12 Projects for 2015 January Screenwriters Lab|last=|first=|date=September 16, 2014|website=Sundance Institute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> DaCosta funded the film through [[Kickstarter]] with the help of 72 backers who eventually raised $5,100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1451542035/little-woods-by-nia-dacosta|title=Little Woods by Nia DaCosta|last=DaCosta|first=Nia|date=December 17, 2014|website=Kickstarter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===''Little Woods''===\n''[[Little Woods]]'' tells the story of Ollie ([[Tessa Thompson]]) a reformed drug runner in rural North Dakota and her estranged sister Deb ([[Lily James]]). When their mother dies, Deb shows up on Ollie's doorstep with her young son, and reveals she is pregnant. This pushes Ollie to seek out a way to quickly raise money to pay back the bank and keep their mother\u2019s home, and pushes Deb to decide whether or not she wants to go through with getting an abortion. \n\nThe film premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]] in 2018, and was awarded the [[Nora Ephron]] award for \"excellence in storytelling by a female writer or director.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tribeca-announces-nora-ephron-award-440516|title=Tribeca Announces Nora Ephron Award|last=Schillaci|first=Sophie|date=April 16, 2013|website=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was then bought by [[Neon (distributor)|Neon]] and distributed through [[North America]] in April of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/little-woods-tessa-thompson-lily-james-nia-dacosta-neon-1202410650/|title=Neon Acquires Nia DaCosta\u2019s \u2018Little Woods\u2019 After Tribeca Bow|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=June 14, 2018|website=Deadline|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> DaCosta cites [[Debra Granik|Debrah Granik's]]  ''[[Winter's Bone]]'' and [[Courtney Hunt|Courtney Hunt's]] ''[[Frozen River]]'' as being her main sources of inspiration for the script, as she feels that their films relay amazing performances and tense drama, yet tackle real issues in America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filminquiry.com/tribeca-review-little-woods/|title=Tribeca Review & Interviews: LITTLE WOODS: A Confident Debut|last=Strouse|first=Kristy|date=May 4, 2018|website=Film Inquiry|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In a 2018 interview with FF2 Media, DaCosta stated the importance to her of telling the stories of \"women...who are active\" rather than passive figures in movies led by men. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Coffin |first1=Lesley |title=Nora Ephron winner Nia DaCosta talks \u2018Little Woods\u2019 |url=http://ff2media.com/blog/2018/04/29/nora-ephron-winner-nia-dacosta-on-little-woods/ |website=FF2 Media |publisher=FF2 Media |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Candyman''===\n{{main|Candyman (2020 film)}}\nIt was announced in late 2018 that DaCosta was chosen to helm what has been described as a [[Spiritual successor|spiritual sequel]] to the original [[Candyman (1992 film)|''Candyman'']] (1992). The film is said to return to the [[Chicago]] neighborhood where the legend began, yet it is now [[Gentrification|gentrified]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/candyman-reboot-nia-dacosta-jordan-peele-1203037897/|title=Jordan Peele-Produced \u2018Candyman\u2019 Reboot Taps Director Nia DaCosta|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=November 27, 2018|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The film is being produced by [[Jordan Peele]] through [[Monkeypaw Productions|Monkeypaw productions]], with Peele citing the original as \"a landmark film for black representation in the horror genre.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]] is set to star in the film,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/jordan-peele-candyman-cast-yahya-abdul-mateen-villain.html|title=Jordan Peele\u2019s Candyman Has Found Its Hook-Handed Villain|last=Crucchiola|first=Jordan|date=February 26, 2019|website=Vulture|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> with [[Tony Todd]] returning as the film's [[Candyman (character)|titular villain]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https:/