| 2012\n| ''Dark Prophet''\n| Agent Noah Parish\n| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2 |2013\n| ''{{sortname|The|Awesomes}}''\n| Perfect Man (voice)\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Awesomes|nolink=1}}''\n| Thug #3 (voice)\n| Episode: \"Baby's Got Backstory\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Charles, Your Hangover''\n| Rickey, the apprentice\n| Episode: \"The Apprentice\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Kings of Con''\n| Kent O'Grady\n| 1 episode\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|583570}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meyers, Josh}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American impressionists (entertainers)]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Czech descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Bedford, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Actors from Manchester, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:American sketch comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Josh Myers}}\n{{For|the ice hockey player|Josh Meyers (ice hockey)}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Joshua Dylan Meyers\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|1|8|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Bedford, New Hampshire]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor, comedian\n| years_active = 2001\u2013present\n| relatives = [[Seth Meyers]] (brother)\n}}\n'''Joshua Dylan Meyers''' ({{IPAc-en|'|m|a\u026a|.|\u0259r|z|}} {{respell|MY|\u0259rz}}; born January 8, 1976) is an American actor and comedian, known for being a cast member of the [[sketch comedy]] series, ''[[Mad TV]]'' and playing Randy Pearson in the eighth and final season of ''[[That '70s Show]]''. He is the younger brother of former ''[[Saturday Night Live|SNL]]'' cast member and ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers|Late Night]]'' host [[Seth Meyers]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMeyers was born in [[Bedford, New Hampshire]]{{fact|date=January 2019}}, on January 8, 1976, the younger of two boys born of Hilary Claire (n\u00e9e Olson), a French teacher, and Laurence Meyers Jr., who worked in finance.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/1946965372.html?FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&type=historic&date=Jul+05%2C+1970&author=&pub=Boston+Globe+(1960-1979)&desc=Miss+Hilary+Olson+marries+Mr.+Meyers&pqatl=google|work=Boston Globe|title=Miss Hilary Olson marries Mr. Meyers|date=July 5, 1970}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20081214/SNLs+Seth+Meyers+Power+Fun|first=Alison|last=Prato|work=[[New York Post]]|title=SNL's Seth Meyers: The Power of Fun |date=December 14, 2008|quote=...a father who worked in finance and a French teacher mom.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217051353/http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20081214/SNLs%2BSeth%2BMeyers%2BPower%2BFun|archivedate=December 17, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe attended [[Manchester High School West]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]]. He went on to graduate from [[Northwestern University]] in [[Evanston, Illinois]]. Meyers' paternal grandfather was [[Jewish]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanisraelite.com/archives/26453|title=Jewz in the Newz|publisher=[[The American Israelite]]|date=2013-07-17|accessdate=2014-02-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131104181946/http://americanisraelite.com/archives/26453|archivedate=2013-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/late-night-with-seth-meyers/video/seths-story-seths-jewish-enough/2776163#I|title=Watch Late Night: Seth Meyers \"Seth's Story: Seth's Jewish Enough\" Highlight - NBC.com|work=NBC|accessdate=May 13, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428220522/http://www.nbc.com/late-night-with-seth-meyers/video/seths-story-seths-jewish-enough/2776163#I|archivedate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> and his other ancestry is Czech\u2013Austrian and Croatian (from his paternal grandmother), Swedish, English, and German.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nate Bloom |url=http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/Interfaith_Celebrities_Glee_News_Seth_Meyers_Gets_Engaged_Baseball_News.shtml|title=Seth Meyers Gets Engaged|publisher=InterfaithFamily|accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===''Mad TV''===\nMeyers officially joined the cast of ''Mad TV'' in 2002, as a featured performer for the eighth season. He would fill in the spot of the Spishak Spokesperson that [[David Herman]] and [[Pat Kilbane]] previously owned. Meyers was also known for his celebrity impersonations, including [[Anna Nicole Smith]]'s son, [[Daniel Wayne Smith|Daniel]], various members of [['N Sync]], rapper [[Eminem]], and actor [[Owen Wilson]].\n\nMeyers's appearances on ''Mad TV'' on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] aired directly opposite his brother [[Seth Meyers|Seth]]'s appearances on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on [[NBC]]. This was referenced on a [[Saturday Night Live (season 28)|season 28]] episode of ''Saturday Night Live'' in which Seth appears on ''[[Weekend Update]]'' to talk to his father and tells him to turn off ''Mad TV'' and pay attention to him.<ref name=JoshMeyersPajiba>{{cite web|last1=Rowles|first1=Dustin|title=Who Remembers That Seth Meyers' Little Brother Replaced Eric and Kelso on ''That '70s Show''?|url=http://www.pajiba.com/seriously_random_lists/who-remembers-that-seth-meyers-little-brother-replaced-eric-and-kelso-on-that-70s-show-.php|website=Pajiba|accessdate=February 22, 2015|date=January 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nWhen [[Topher Grace]] left ''[[That '70s Show]]'' at the end of the show's seventh season, Meyers was chosen as a replacement, starring as Randy Pearson during the [[That '70s Show (season 8)|eighth and final season]].<ref name=JoshMeyersPajiba /> In 2006, Meyers made an appearance in the feature film ''[[Date Movie]]'', where he plays [[Napoleon Dynamite]] and [[Owen Wilson]]'s character from ''[[Wedding Crashers]]''.\n\nMeyers has a supporting role in the 2008 film ''[[College Road Trip]]'', and appeared alongside [[Pee-wee Herman]] in the 2010 stage show revival of ''{{sortname|The|Pee-wee Herman Show on Broadway|The Pee-wee Herman Show#2010 stage show revival}}''.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film\n! Year\n! style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Down (film)|Down]]''\n| ESU cop #5\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''Snapshots''\n| Hooligan in red light district\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''{{sortname|The|Adventures of Big Handsome Guy and His Little Friend|nolink=1}}''\n| Bar jerk\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Date Movie]]''\n| [[Napoleon Dynamite]]/[[Owen Wilson]] look-alike\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Wrangling Coach Rankin''\n| Josh\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[College Road Trip]]''\n| Stuart\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Br\u00fcno]]''\n| Kookus\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[How to Make Love to a Woman]]''\n| Andy Conners\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 |2013\n| ''[[Straight A's]]''\n| Jason\n|\n|-\n| ''Inventing Adam''\n| Adam\n|\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Sidekick|nolink=1}}''\n| Jimmy T\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''Cafe Attitude''\n| {{n/a}}\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Going to America (film)|Going to America]]''\n| Andy\n|\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2002\u20132004\n| ''[[Mad TV]]''\n| Various\n| 47 episodes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Half & Half]]''\n| Big Fat Slim Jim\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Life as We Know It (TV