a]]\n[[Category:Fictional karateka]]\n[[Category:Fictional KGB agents]]\n[[Category:Fictional Ninjutsu practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n[[Category:Fictional savateurs]]\n[[Category:Fictional Soviet people]]\n[[Category:Fictional special forces personnel]]\n[[Category:Fictional women soldiers and warriors]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics female superheroes]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics superheroes]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics martial artists]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Marvel vs. Capcom fighters]]\n[[Category:Russian superheroes]]\n[[Category:S.H.I.E.L.D. agents]]\n[[Category:Superhero film characters]]\n", "name_user": "Caitcat3211", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Widow_(Natasha_Romanova)"}
{"title_page": "Alex Buncombe", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n|name        = Alex Buncombe\n|image       =\n|caption     =\n|nationality = {{flagicon|GBR}} [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|birth_name  = \n|birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|28 August 1981}}\n|birth_place = [[Taunton]], England}}\n\n'''Alex Buncombe''' (born 28 August 1981 in [[Taunton]], England) is a British racing driver, recently left RJN Motorsport after the [[Blancpain Endurance Series]]. He is a part of the [[Nismo Global Driver Exchange]], working with [[Nissan]] and RJN Motorsport to provide graduates of the [[Gran Turismo (series)#GT Academy|GT Academy program]] with guidance and helping them to develop their motor racing skills. He is the brother of [[Chris Buncombe]].\n\n==Career==\nBuncombe competed in the [[British Formula Renault Championship#Formula Renault 2.0 UK|British Formula Renault Championship]] from 2001 to 2003, finishing fifth in the 2003 Winter Series.<ref name=\"DriverDB\">{{cite web | url=https://www.driverdb.com/drivers/alex-buncombe/ | title=Alex Buncombe | publisher=Driver Database | accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref> He took part in his first [[Sports car racing|GT race]] in 2005, competing in the [[Trofeo Maserati]]. He won his first race in the series, at [[Autodromo Nazionale Monza|Monza]], by thirty-five seconds.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nissannews.com/en-US/nissan/usa/releases/alex-buncombe-nissan-s-secret-weapon | title=Alex Buncombe: Nissan's Secret Weapon | work=NissanNews.com | date=12 October 2012 | accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref> From 2007 to 2011, Buncombe competed in the [[GT4 European Series]] for RJN Motorsport. He finished third in 2007 before finishing as runner-up in 2008 and 2009. He continued to drive in the series until 2011. In total he scored five pole positions and ten wins.<ref name=\"DriverDB\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://gt4cup.com/teaminfo.php?teamname=RJN%20Motorsport | title=RJN Motorsport | publisher=Avon GT4 Trophy | accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBuncombe has competed in the Blancpain Endurance Series since 2011, winning the GT4 Cup class that season along with [[Jordan Tresson]] and Christopher Ward. The GT4 Cup class was removed from the series the following year and Buncombe moved into the GT3 Pro-Am Cup class. Buncombe has scored two wins and recorded a best season finish of fourth in 2013.<ref name=\"DriverDB\" />\n\nBuncombe has taken part in various endurance races since 2008, including the [[Bathurst 12 Hour]] and the [[Dubai 24 Hour|Dubai]], [[24 Hours N\u00fcrburgring|N\u00fcrburgring]], [[Silverstone Britcar 24-Hour|Silverstone]] and [[Spa 24 Hours|Spa]] 24 hour races.<ref name=\"DriverDB\" /><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/motorsport/8048245/Britcar-24-Hours-race-review.html | title=Britcar 24 Hours race review | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | last=Meaden | first=Richard | date=8 October 2010 | accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailysportscar.com/2014/07/07/nissan-shuffles-the-pack-for-spa-24-hours.html | title=Nissan Shuffles the Pack for Spa 24 Hours | work=DailySportsCar.com | date=7 July 2014 | accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Buncombe Chiyo Kelly Reip Nissan 2014 Bathurst 12HR.JPG|thumb|250px|The Nissan GT-R of Buncombe, Chiyo, Kelly and Reip at the 2014 Bathurst 12 Hour.]]\n\n===Australia===\nBuncombe competed in the [[2014 Liqui Moly Bathurst 12 Hour|2014 Bathurst 12 Hour]] as part of the [[Nismo Global Driver Exchange]], driving a [[Nissan GT-R|Nissan GT-R Nismo GT3]] with [[Katsumasa Chiyo]], [[Rick Kelly]] and Wolfgang Reip. Chiyo was involved in a crash in the early stages of the race, ending the team's chances after 58 laps.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.speedcafe.com/2014/02/09/lowndes-holds-bathurst-thriller/ | title=Lowndes holds on in Bathurst thriller | work=Speedcafe | date=9 February 2014 | accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref> Buncombe was scheduled to return to the race for [[2015 Liqui Moly Bathurst 12 Hour|2015]], but was forced to withdraw due to the impending birth of his first child.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2015/_STORY/150203-01-e.html | title=Florian Strauss to replace Alex Buncombe for Nissan at 2015 Bathurst 12 Hour | work=Nissan Global | date=3 February 2015 | accessdate=20 February 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215073834/http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2015/_STORY/150203-01-e.html | archive-date=15 February 2015 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2014 Bathurst 12 Hour, Buncombe joined [[Nissan Motorsport (Australia)|Nissan's V8 Supercar team]] as a co-driver for [[Todd Kelly]] in the [[2014 International V8 Supercars Championship#Pirtek Endurance Cup|2014 Endurance Cup]]. The pair finished twentieth at the [[2014 Wilson Security Sandown 500|Sandown 500]] before recording a creditable seventh-place finish at the [[2014 Supercheap Auto Bathurst 1000|Bathurst 1000]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.speedcafe.com/2014/09/14/whincupdumbrell-take-commanding-sandown-win/ | title=Whincup/Dumbrell take commanding Sandown win | work=Speedcafe | date=14 September 2014 | accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.speedcafe.com/2014/10/12/mostertmorris-win-eight-hour-bathurst-thriller/ | title=Mostert/Morris win eight-hour Bathurst thriller | work=Speedcafe | date=12 October 2014 | accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Racing record==\n\n===Career summary===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%; text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Series\n! Team\n! Races\n! Wins\n! Poles\n! {{tooltip|FLaps|Fastest laps}}\n! Podiums\n! Points\n! Position\n|-\n! 2001\n| align=\"left\"| [[British Formula Renault Championship#Formula Renault 2.0 UK|Formula Renault UK]]\n| align=\"left\"| Aztec International\n| 8\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 54\n| 23rd\n|